*  Practical Online Improvement of Pretrained Policies for Robitic Manipulation
- Date :: 11/21/2025
- Event :: THEORY SEMINAR
- Author :: Andrew 

This talk about how Reinforcement Learning Deployment could be improved if their performance is
not satisfactory.

** Typical Behavioral
- We record some human action such as taking an object
- We train a Neural Network model to mimic said action
- We deploy and test the model

This works if the environment is free of noise, which is never the case. Many of these models are very
sensitive to noise and any divergence from their training may cause severe degradation of performance.

** What can we do when we fail?
- Start over with more human data?
- There are situations in which starting over doesn't work
  

The situation above seems like a good place to use Reinforcement Learning. We have a action-reward mechanism and
we would want the model to learn using this reward mechanism. But the huge requirement of samples may be a limiting
factor in adopting RL.

The rest of the talk is split amongst the following two topics:

1. Online Learning
2. How to pretrain models so that they are more amenable to the above online learning



** Online Learning

The RL models in the following discussions will be all diffusion models.
- Given a diffusion model in deployment how can we improve its peformance?
- The key technique the authors use to improve the sampling of the noise space.
- They treat the Diffusion policy as a black box mapping from noise space to action space.
- Usually the noise space is Gaussian. Could there be an avenue for improvement in how we sample from this noise space?
- They found that optimizing the noise space instead of the action space improves peformance


** Pretraining
- Is there a way to make the Diffusion policies more amenable to the above technique?
- They found a way to augment data with entropy. On data regions with low samples they augment with entropy and data regions
  with high number of samples are augmented to a lesser degree. This process makes the RL model to have a degree of freedom
  which can then be improved through online learning


** Conclusion
This work was about deployment of RL policies in robotics, specifically robots which attempts to mimic human actions such as turning on
a toaster. They author presented a new way to improve performance of a RL model and how one could make a more suitable for such an
online learning.
  

